passages.text: August 31, 2025 08:00 PM GMT

FY25 result season closes. Index pushing all time highs whilst market earnings levels plumb low. Large cap volatility on show, small caps outperform. Selective defense wins whilst rotation still an open debate. Domestic policy evolution topical whilst global macro influence sustains.

What's topical? It's all in the price: In our view the FY25e result season was one of the trickier ones to navigate in recent times. Whilst beats and misses have been broadly in- line relative to MS estimates, extreme volatility in well known and well owned large caps complicated the search for alpha in a market that breached for a time the key 9000 level and established new all- time highs in the process. The multiple paid is at odds with earnings on offer. Aggregate EPS levels are anchored at multi- year lows, FY25 will likely finish at negative growth and FY26 EPSg has fallen to 4.5% (from 7.2% as at Dec- 31, 2024). Further progress to our Bull case targets requires an earnings lift (which outlooks have not triggered) so in the meantime we expect a degree of both market and intra- sector rotation as the pieces on the chessboard are moved. The best sectors and stocks in the month were Materials, Discretionary and Real Estate while laggards included Health Care and Technology. Small caps outperformed large by 4.8% with strong Materials performance and also domestic policy support a key driver. Global macro influence stays front of mind with the bear case linking to inflation rather than growth concerns but that is not a domestically sourced risk at this juncture (more below).

Macro Catalysts - Building Approvals (Jul), GDP (Q2), Household Spending Indicator (Jul), Trade Balance (Jul): We expect a softer building approvals prior for July, falling - 5.0%M (9.6%Y). We expect GDP to have increased 0.6%Q in Q2 to stand 1.7% higher than a year ago. We expect household spending will have increased 0.6%M in July, with the annual rate pushed to 5.2%Y - the strongest seen since Jan- 24. We expect the trade balance will come in at an A\\$5bn surplus.

Last Week - July CPI, Q2 Private Sector Capex, July Private Sector Credit: Headline CPI beat consensus expectations in July, increasing to 2.8%Y - the highest annual rate since Jul- 24. Core inflation also increased from 2.1%Y to 2.7%. The print was much stronger than we or consensus expected, although most of the beat was driven by timing issues (electricity) and volatile categories (travel). Capex spending increased 0.2%Q in Q2, softer than MS/consensus expectations however with the annual rate pushed to 1.7%Y. Private Sector Credit for July increased 0.7%M, pushing the annual rate to 7.0%Y.

Keeping Score - The ASX closed up this week (+0.1% WoW); Materials led while Communication Services was the notable laggard. ASX 200 12MF multiple remains elevated at 19.9x, +2 SD above its long- term average of 14.8x. Aggregate consensus EPS growth estimates for FY25 and FY26 are - 3.1% and +4.5%, respectively.

This Season Has Passed: Results have closed broadly in- line when comparing beats to misses for earnings and revenue relative to MS estimates, whilst DPS have surprised to the upside with 1.6x more beats than misses. Price reaction relative to history and February 2025 results had been tracking at a much narrower range at three- quarter time, though over the past week reported results had seen this widen with earnings beats on average having outperformed the market (ASX 300) by \(+3.9\%\) , whilst misses have underperformed by \(- 2.6\%\) . Revenue misses have been punished more (- 4.0%) than beats have been rewarded (+1.5%). See charts below for more detail.
Our analysis for the August 2025 reporting season includes those companies that have reported full- year (FY25) or interim (1H/2H FY25) results for key stocks under coverage.

Breached Not Broken? The ASX 200 eclipsed the 9000 level on August 21, 2025 before settling back marginally below this important psychological level. The total return for the market this calendar year is \(12.4\%\) and the rally from April lows is \(23.5\%\) . Our base case target remains 8500 and the Bull case is 9350 – but our upside scenarios are linked to better earnings not necessarily higher prices. To us it is clear that Australian equities have followed the multiple expansion of markets like the US, but unlike the US the aggregate earnings pulse this season has been weak. The FY25 base now looks to settle at negative \(3.1\%\) EPS growth and so far aggregate earnings have remained anchored at low levels. FY26e bottom- up consensus calls for circa \(4.5\%\) growth – possibly a low bar but not being challenged by outlook statements at this stage of the cycle.

Think Big, Buy Small: Small caps enjoyed a better results season vs large caps over the month of August. In part this was due to large (indeed small cap like) drawdowns in a number of larger weighted names in big caps and also the buy into emerging earnings opportunity and favourable domestic (policy- assisted) backdrops that small caps leveraged. Also within Smalls, the Materials sector saw strong outperformance up \(14.9\%\) and within that the gold sector was a major driver. Overall Small caps for the month are up \(7.5\%\) vs mid caps at \(5.0\%\) vs large at \(2.7\%\) .

Winners and Losers: In large caps the best sectors were Materials, Discretionary and Real Estate and the laggards were Health Care and Technology. Top performing stocks included IEL, PLS, LYC, MIN and NST whilst the underperformers were TLX, JHX, CSL, REH and WTC. In small caps, Materials, Technology and Discretionary were sector leaders, whilst sectors that lagged included Health Care, Communication Services and Staples. Top performing stocks in small caps were CRN, TUA, VAU, CDA and CYL; conversely those with outsized drawdowns included CU6, SKC, AD8, ING and EBO.

House Prices for August (1 Sep): We expect house prices will have ticked higher in August, tracking around the same growth rate as the prior month with Perth and Brisbane likely leading. We expect house prices to remain supported through the rest of the year, as delivery of two rate cuts, as well as expectation of more, helps to support sentiment and activity (construction/turnover).

Building Approvals for July (1 Sep): We expect a softer building approvals print for July, falling \(- 5.0\% M\) (9.6%Y). Strength in June was driven by apartments which are generally noisy, and so a partial payback in July is likely. Nevertheless this would still be annualizing \(\sim 195k\) approvals, broadly consistent with our expectation for a pickup in the construction side of the housing market as rate cuts help to support activity.

GDP for Q2 (3 Sep): We expect GDP to have increased \(0.6\% Q\) in Q2, to be \(1.7\%\) higher than a year ago. This represents a modest acceleration in both quarterly and annual terms. Much of the delta is expected to be a sharp pick-up in public spending, which was weak the prior quarter, but we also expect some improvement in consumption spending and a small increase in private investment. Net exports are expected to have a flat contribution in the quarter.

Household Spending Indicator for July (4 Sep): We expect household spending will have increased \(0.6\% M\) in July, with the annual rate pushed to \(5.2\% Y\) - the strongest seen since Jan- 24. We expect strength in recreation/hospitality with several busy sporting events being held in July. Goods may see some payback following a stronger June where consumers took advantage of EOFY sales.

Trade Balance for July (4 Sep): We expect the trade balance will come in at an A\$5bn surplus in July, broadly in line with the June level. We would expect some payback in capital goods which were particularly weak in June.

July CPI: Alert, But Not Alarmed (27 Aug 2025): Headline CPI beat MS/consensus expectations in July, increasing to \(2.8\% Y-\) the highest annual rate since Jul- 24. Core inflation also increased from \(2.1\% Y\) to \(2.7\%\) . Boosts to inflation came from Electricity and Recreation (Travel). ABS called out strong school holiday demand/higher prices for airfares and accommodation. Large jump in electricity costs \((- 6.3\% Y\) to \(13.1\% Y)\) looks mostly temporary - households in NSW/ACT did not receive extended EBRF payments. Expect payback in Aug. Building construction costs also ticked higher in the month; we stay alert for any signs of re- acceleration. Nevertheless mix excl. volatile categories were slightly more favourable with Rents down (lowest annual growth rate since Nov- 22) & Health/Education/Insurance stable.
